    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1918-08-02T12:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1918-08-02T12:00:00-05:00" n="79"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d79">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 600.119/1095</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Great Britain</hi> (<persName
                        corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_PWH1" type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Page</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1918-08-02T18:00:00+01:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">August 2, 1918, 6 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received 6.35 p.m.</hi>]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>810. War Trade Board [from <persName corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_SLP1"
                        >Sheldon</persName>]:</p>
                <p>No. 1156. Referring to your’886, Department’s 292, July 17 [<hi rend="italic"
                        >18</hi>], 7 p.m., Foreign Office think the principle announced is
                    undoubtedly a sound one to which the Swedes should not take any objection. I
                    have talked over the matter of coffee with Mr. <persName
                        corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_MIN1">Morris</persName>, our Minister at
                    Stockholm, who is now in London, and learned from him that there is considerable
                    dissatisfaction in Sweden owing to our unwillingness to permit unconditional
                    export of coffee previously bought in the United States. I have pointed out to
                    him that in the covering letter to the Swedish agreement,<note n="2"
                        xml:id="d79fn2">
                        <hi rend="italic">Post</hi>, <ref target="#pg_1264">p. 1264</ref>.</note>
                    paragraph 3 specifies a number of commodities which Sweden will be permitted to
                    purchase in the United States and obtain export licenses according to rations.
                    Some of these commodities are not indigenous to the United States and the Swedes
                    never mentioned a desire to include coffee in this <pb facs="0156" n="990"
                        xml:id="pg_990"/> list. I would suggest that if the Associated Governments
                    come to an agreement in regard to asking payment at the par value of kroner for
                    commodities purchased in any of the Associated countries, and so inform the
                    Swedish and Norwegian Governments, as well as any other neutral with whom we
                    have or may have an agreement [<hi rend="italic">sic</hi>]. It would be
                    appropriate to include therewith a statement of your plan mentioned in your 886.
                    I think no objection would be taken to these principles if great care were taken
                    in the wording of the announcement and the application of the principles, and I
                    suggest that you take both these matters up with the other Allied
                    Governments.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_PWH1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Page</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
